layout_mode = 2

[node name="TutorialContents" type="Label" parent="TutorialManual/VBoxContainer/ScrollContainer/HBoxContainer" unique_id=1951936389]
custom_minimum_size = Vector2(900, 300)
layout_mode = 2
theme_override_fonts/font = ExtResource("2_ttshj")
theme_override_font_sizes/font_size = 20
text = "Controls:
A and D to move left and right
Left and Right arrow keys to move left and right for red team in local PVP
W key to jump, spike, receive
Up arrow key to jump, spike, receive for red team in local PVP

When receiving, the ball has to be close to the receiver, and
then either the W or Up arrow key is pressed.

Spiking also requires the ball to be close. To spike, press the W key
to jump first, then press the W key again once the player is close to
the ball.

You can also control where your spike hits. 
Hold the A or D keys (or left/right arrow keys for
local PVP) to spike the ball closer to the net or 
farther. Whether it goes closer or farther will 
depend on which button you are holding, as shown in the images to the side.

Rules:
Each game initially goes up to 10 points. so in a situation where
the score is 10 : 8, the game would go to the team with 10 points.
However, the winning team has to have 2 more points than the opposing team. 
If, for example, the team scores are 10 : 9, then they would play another round.
If it becomes 10 : 10, they would play again, since neither team 
has a 2 point advantage. This would continue until one team has
2 points greater than the other team (for example, 12 : 10).

After a long rally, the ball will get faster with each successive spike
to make high level gameplay more challenging.

If the ball is hit out (past the white barriers on each side of the court),
then the point goes to the opposing team.

You cannot receive using the spiker, or spike with the receiver.

If a spiker fails to hit the ball on their jump, they cannot jump again.

If the ball hits the net, it is considered to still be in play
until it has hit the floor.

Tips:
You can always adjust the computer's difficulty level in the options menu.

When receiving, the ball always goes to the same place,
right next to and above the net. This means that when spiking,
you can move there and know for certain that you will
be able to hit it if you time it right.

When you spike, try to jump early, as during the jump, the ball
will continue moving. By jumping early, you can intercept the ball 
rather than finding that the ball has already moved by the time you
get enough height.

You can start holding down the movement key (A, D, left, or right)
during the short pause that happens when the opponent spikes, 
and you will immediately start moving as soon as the pause is over,
allowing you to move to receive easier.

Wow, you actually read all of that!
Here's a happy face for you :)
And a bit of knowledge: there is one easter egg in this game.
See if you can find where it is!"

